{#
  Color-evolution panel — static shell. The curves are computed entirely
  client-side from the live light-curve chart's GP bundle (`color_evolution.js`
  reads `$lcGp` — the per-band posterior flux grid + `cov_offdiag` band-band
  covariances — on the canvas referenced by `data-lc-target`). Adjacent-band
  colors (u−g, g−r, …) are formed in magnitudes and their errors propagated
  with the FULL band-band covariance (not the marginal per-band σ).

  This slot shares the residuals grid cell and is auto-shown over Position
  Residuals whenever the GP overlay is active (see lightcurve.js `lc:gpChanged`
  + `window.lcGpState`), reverting when GP is deselected.
#}
<div
  data-color-panel
  data-lc-target="lc-canvas-{{ oid }}"
  data-ce-mode="time"
  class="tw-h-full tw-flex tw-flex-col tw-bg-bg-card tw-border tw-border-border tw-rounded tw-p-4"
>
  <div class="tw-flex tw-items-center tw-justify-between tw-mb-2 tw-gap-3">
    {% from "_panel_help.html.jinja" import panel_help %}
    {% call panel_help("Color evolution", side="right") %}
      <div class="tw-font-semibold tw-mb-1">What's plotted</div>
      <p class="tw-mb-3 tw-text-text-secondary">Adjacent-band colors (u−g, g−r, r−i, i−z, z−Y) derived from the Gaussian-Process light-curve fit, in magnitudes. <span class="mono">vs Time</span> shows each color's evolution with a shaded ±1σ band; <span class="mono">Color–color</span> plots one color against another, points colored by time.</p>
      <div class="tw-font-semibold tw-mb-1">Why the GP</div>
      <p class="tw-mb-3 tw-text-text-secondary">The colors come from the joint multi-band GP posterior, so even bands sampled at different epochs give a color at every time. A color is <span class="mono">−2.5·log₁₀(F<sub>blue</sub>/F<sub>red</sub>)</span> from the posterior mean fluxes.</p>
      <div class="tw-font-semibold tw-mb-1">Errors use the GP covariance</div>
      <p class="tw-mb-3 tw-text-text-secondary">Two bands fit by one GP are correlated; the color error uses the proper band-band covariance <span class="mono">Σ<sub>br</sub></span>, not the marginal per-band σ — <span class="mono">Var(C)=a²[V<sub>b</sub>/F<sub>b</sub>²+V<sub>r</sub>/F<sub>r</sub>²−2Σ<sub>br</sub>/(F<sub>b</sub>F<sub>r</sub>)]</span>. In color–color view the points carry proper 1σ <em>ellipses</em>: a shared band (e.g. r in g−r vs r−i) tilts the ellipse.</p>
      <div class="tw-font-semibold tw-mb-1">Notes</div>
      <ul class="tw-space-y-0.5 tw-mb-3 tw-list-disc tw-list-inside tw-text-text-secondary">
        <li>Dereddening (Der) shifts each color by −(R<sub>blue</sub>−R<sub>red</sub>)·E(B−V); the distance modulus cancels in a color.</li>
        <li>Points where a band's flux isn't significantly positive (SNR&lt;2) are dropped — a color needs a real magnitude.</li>
        <li>Bands hidden in the Light-curve legend drop out here too; fold the LC (Sci) to get colors over phase.</li>
        <li>Color–color view: drag the two handles on the time colorbar to restrict the epochs shown — useful to cut a noisy early/late phase. The colorbar min/max and the point colors follow the selected window.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="tw-font-semibold tw-mb-1">Navigation</div>
      <ul class="tw-space-y-0.5 tw-list-disc tw-list-inside tw-text-text-secondary">
        <li>Zoom: mouse wheel · Box-zoom: drag · Pan: <span class="mono">Ctrl</span>+drag · Reset: double-click</li>
      </ul>
    {% endcall %}
    <div class="tw-flex tw-items-center tw-gap-3">
      <div
        data-ce-status
        class="tw-text-text-muted tw-text-xs"
        title="Live summary of the colors currently plotted."
      ></div>
      <div data-ce-cc-controls class="tw-hidden tw-flex tw-items-center tw-gap-1 tw-text-xs">
        <select
          data-ce-xpair
          class="tw-bg-bg-card tw-border tw-border-border tw-rounded tw-text-text-primary tw-text-xs tw-px-1 tw-py-0.5"
          title="Color on the X axis"
        ></select>
        <span class="tw-text-text-muted">vs</span>
        <select
          data-ce-ypair
          class="tw-bg-bg-card tw-border tw-border-border tw-rounded tw-text-text-primary tw-text-xs tw-px-1 tw-py-0.5"
          title="Color on the Y axis"
        ></select>
      </div>
      <button
        type="button"
        data-ce-mode-btn
        class="tw-px-2 tw-py-0.5 tw-text-xs tw-border tw-border-border tw-rounded tw-bg-bg-card tw-text-text-muted hover:tw-text-text-primary"
        title="Switch between color-vs-time and color-color views."
      >vs Time</button>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="js-scroll-shield tw-relative tw-flex-1 tw-min-h-0">
    <canvas
      id="color-evolution-canvas-{{ oid }}"
      class="color-evolution-canvas"
    ></canvas>
  </div>
  <div data-ce-colorbar class="tw-mt-2 tw-hidden">
    {# Dual-handle window slider (neutral track) sits ABOVE the colorbar. The
       colorbar (data-ce-bar) always shows the FULL viridis colormap, but drawn
       only across the window's width (the rest dimmed grey); points are colored
       over the same window so they use the full colour scale. As the handles
       move, the colored band narrows/moves and the points recolor to match. The
       endpoint labels sit under the colored band. #}
    <div class="ce-slider tw-relative" style="height: 14px;">
      <div
        class="tw-absolute tw-left-0 tw-right-0 tw-rounded"
        style="top: 50%; transform: translateY(-50%); height: 4px; background: #333333;"
      ></div>
      <input data-ce-tmin class="ce-range" type="range" min="0" max="1000" value="0"
             aria-label="Minimum time shown" />
      <input data-ce-tmax class="ce-range" type="range" min="0" max="1000" value="1000"
             aria-label="Maximum time shown" />
    </div>
    <div
      data-ce-bar
      class="tw-mt-1 tw-rounded"
      style="height: 8px; background: linear-gradient(to right, #440154, #3b528b, #21908c, #5dc863, #fde725);"
    ></div>
    <div
      data-ce-range
      class="tw-flex tw-items-center tw-justify-between tw-text-[10px] tw-text-text-muted tw-mt-1"
    ></div>
  </div>
</div>
<style>
  /* Two overlapping range inputs forming a dual-handle window slider over a
     neutral track. Transparent input tracks; only the thumbs capture pointer
     events so either handle stays grabbable even when they overlap. */
  [data-color-panel] .ce-slider .ce-range {
    position: absolute; left: 0; top: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0;
    background: transparent; pointer-events: none;
    -webkit-appearance: none; appearance: none;
  }
  [data-color-panel] .ce-slider .ce-range::-webkit-slider-runnable-track { background: transparent; height: 100%; }
  [data-color-panel] .ce-slider .ce-range::-moz-range-track { background: transparent; height: 100%; }
  [data-color-panel] .ce-slider .ce-range::-webkit-slider-thumb {
    -webkit-appearance: none; pointer-events: auto; cursor: ew-resize;
    height: 14px; width: 14px; margin-top: 0; border-radius: 9999px;
    background: #f0f6fc; border: 2px solid #1f6feb; box-shadow: 0 0 2px rgba(0,0,0,.6);
  }
  [data-color-panel] .ce-slider .ce-range::-moz-range-thumb {
    pointer-events: auto; cursor: ew-resize;
    height: 14px; width: 14px; border-radius: 9999px;
    background: #f0f6fc; border: 2px solid #1f6feb; box-shadow: 0 0 2px rgba(0,0,0,.6);
  }
</style>
